<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06067240 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06067240 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Mr. Bundesen  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  OBITUARY; SPACE; VEHICLE; TECHNOLOGY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A memorial service will be conducted Friday for Allen E. Bundesen, 56, who wasa descendant of early-day Santa Clara County families and who worked on thePolaris-Poseidon-Trident missile program for Lockheed Missiles andamp; Space Co.;   He died Sunday at his home in Elk Grove while awaiting a heart transplant. Hehad lived in the San Jose area until two years ago when he moved to Elk Grove.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  A. BUNDESEN, MISSILE SPECIALIST  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Mr. Bundesen was born in Gilroy and grew up on the Fountain Oaks Ranch inMorgan Hill, where his father was the estate foreman for Gertrude Achilles, anheir to the Eastman Kodak fortune.;    Mr. Bundesen's late mother, Lorena, wasborn on the old Montague Ranch, near what is now the intersection of MontagueExpressway and Highway 101 in Santa Clara, and his grandparents, the Bundesensand the Fowlers, were ranchers in Santa Clara and San Martin.;    Afterattending Live Oak High School in Morgan Hill, he went on to San Jose StateUniversity and graduated from the University of San Francisco. He was employedfor 25 years at Lockheed, where he received recognition from the Navy for hiswork on the fleet ballistic missile program.;    Mr. Bundesen was often calledon by his colleagues to help solve problems during development and testing ofmissiles, said his stepson, William Silvius of San Jose.;    Mr. Bundesen alsois survived by his wife, Faye, of Elk Grove, two sons, Theodore A. Bundesenand Eric E. Bundesen, both of San Jose; two other stepsons, David Silvius andEdward Silvius, both of San Jose; a sister, Helen Mark, of San Jose, and threegrandchildren.;    The service is scheduled for 11 a.m. at WestminsterPresbyterian Church, 110 Shasta Ave., San Jose. Disposition of Mr. Bundesen'scremated remains will be private.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910307  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  300  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday March 7, 199100067240,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>